To create a simple Unity game with a top-down view and ML Agents, follow the steps below:

1. Create a new Unity project with 2D template.

2. In the "Assets" panel, right-click and select "Create > Folder", name it "Scripts", and similarly create folders named "Scenes" and "Prefabs".

3. Create a new scene (File > New Scene), and save it in the "Scenes" folder.

4. Create a new "GameObject" in the hierarchy, and name it "Player". Ensure that it has a "Circle Collider 2D" and "Rigidbody2D" components attached.

5. Right-click on the "Scripts" folder and select "Create > C# Script", name it "PlayerController", double-click to open it in an editor, and replace the contents with the following code:

```csharp
using System.Collections;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using UnityEngine;

public class PlayerController : MonoBehaviour
{
    public float speed = 5f;

    private Rigidbody2D rb;

    void Start()
    {
        rb = GetComponent<Rigidbody2D>();
    }

    void FixedUpdate()
    {
        float moveHorizontal = Input.GetAxis("Horizontal");
        float moveVertical = Input.GetAxis("Vertical");

        Vector2 movement = new Vector2(moveHorizontal, moveVertical);

        rb.AddForce(movement * speed);
    }
}
```

6. Drag and drop the "PlayerController" script onto the Player GameObject in the scene.

7. Go to "Window > Package Manager" and import the Unity ML-Agents package if you haven't already.

8. Create another GameObject in the hierarchy and name it "Food". Give it a "Circle Collider 2D" and an "Is Trigger" ticked.

9. Add a new script "Food" in the "Scripts" folder. Open and replace with the following code:

```csharp
using System.Collections;
using System.Collections.Generic;
using UnityEngine;

public class Food : MonoBehaviour
{
    private void OnTriggerEnter2D(Collider2D collision)
    {
        if (collision.CompareTag("Player"))
        {
            Destroy(this.gameObject);
        }
    }
}
```

10. Drag and drop the "Food" script onto the Food GameObject in the scene. Set the Tag of Player GameObject to "Player" from the Inspector.

11. Create a "Training Area" GameObject in the scene, and add the "Behavior Parameters" and "Decision Requester" components to it.

12. In the Assets folder, create another folder named "Brains". Right-click in it > Create > ML-Agents > Learning Brain, name it "PlayerBrain".

13. Configure the Behavior Parameters of the Training Area like this:

    - Behavior Name: "PlayerLearning"
    - Vector Observation > Space Size: 2
    - Actions > Space Type: Continuous
    - Actions > Space Size: 2
    - Model: Drag "PlayerBrain" here

14. Configure Decision Requester as follows:

    - Decision Period: 5
    - Take Actions Between Decisions: True

15. Modify the "PlayerController" script to accept signals from the ML-Agents. Replace the entire code with the following:

```csharp
using UnityEngine;
using Unity.MLAgents;
using Unity.MLAgents.Actuators;
using Unity.MLAgents.Sensors;

public class PlayerController : Agent
{
    public float speed = 5f;
    private Rigidbody2D rb;

    private void Start()
    {
        rb = GetComponent<Rigidbody2D>();
    }

    public override void OnEpisodeBegin()
    {
        rb.velocity = Vector2.zero;
    }

    public override void CollectObservations(VectorSensor sensor)
    {
        sensor.AddObservation(rb.velocity.x);
        sensor.AddObservation(rb.velocity.y);
    }

    public override void OnActionReceived(ActionBuffers actions)
    {
        float moveHorizontal = actions.ContinuousActions[0];
        float moveVertical = actions.ContinuousActions[1];

        Vector2 movement = new Vector2(moveHorizontal, moveVertical);
        rb.AddForce(movement * speed);

        SetReward(-Time.fixedDeltaTime);
    }

    public override void Heuristic(in ActionBuffers actionsOut)
    {
        var continuousActionsOut = actionsOut.ContinuousActions;
        continuousActionsOut[0] = Input.GetAxis("Horizontal");
        continuousActionsOut[1] = Input.GetAxis("Vertical");
    }
}
```

16. Add a new script named "FoodSpawner" in the "Scripts" folder. Open and replace with the following code:

```csharp
using System.Collections;
using UnityEngine;

public class FoodSpawner : MonoBehaviour
{
    public GameObject foodPrefab;
    public int numberOfFoods;
    public float spawnRange;

    void Start()
    {
        SpawnFood();
    }

    void SpawnFood()
    {
        for (int i = 0; i < numberOfFoods; i++)
        {
            Vector2 spawnPosition = new Vector2(Random.Range(-spawnRange, spawnRange), Random.Range(-spawnRange, spawnRange));
            Instantiate(foodPrefab, spawnPosition, Quaternion.identity, transform);
        }
    }
}
```

17. Drag and drop this script onto the "Training Area" GameObject.

18. Create Food prefab and set up FoodSpawner:

    - Drag the Food GameObject from the hierarchy window into the "Prefabs" folder to create a prefab.
    - Select the "Training Area" GameObject, drag and drop the Food prefab to foodPrefab field in FoodSpawner

19. Create a "config.yaml" file in the Assets folder:

```
behaviors:
  PlayerLearning:
    trainer_type: ppo
    max_steps: 100000
    time_horizon: 64
    learning_rate: 0.0003
    batch_size: 128
    buffer_size: 4096
    discount: 0.99
    beta: 0.01
    strength: 0.5
    steps_until_spawn: 0
    summary_freq: 1000
```

20. Train the agent:

    - In the terminal, navigate to the folder containing the Unity project.
    - Inside the project directory, run `mlagents-learn config.yaml --run-id=my_run_1`
    - In Unity, go to the menu Edit > Project Settings > Player > Other Settings, and change the Scripting Backend to "Mono".
    - Click the Play button in Unity to begin training.

After training, you can use the saved neural network model to make the agent move with learned behavior.

1. In the Assets/Brains folder, find your trained model (named "PlayerLearning.nn"), drag and drop it onto the Model field in Behavior Parameters.

2. Press play in Unity, and your agent should now move with the learned behavior. If you want to switch back to keyboard control, you can do so by changing the Behavior Type field in the Behavior Parameters component from "Default" to "Heuristic Only".

