```

After making these changes, re-run the game, and you should not encounter any warnings or errors when eating all the food. The player's episode will reset properly after eating all the food without any stack overflow issues or incorrectly hiding base class methods.

To set a time limit for episodes, you can modify the FoodSpawner script to keep track of episode time. You already have a variable `maxEpisodeTime` defined in the script; you can adjust this in the Unity editor to set the desired time limit in seconds.

To ensure agent episodes end correctly when you have multiple Training Areas, you'll need to make some adjustments to the "PlayerController" and "FoodSpawner" scripts.

1. Update the "PlayerController" script to reference its own "FoodSpawner":

```csharp
private FoodSpawner foodSpawner;

private void Start()
{
    rb = GetComponent<Rigidbody2D>();
    foodSpawner = transform.parent.GetComponentInChildren<FoodSpawner>();
}  
```

Replace `FindObjectOfType<FoodSpawner>()` with `transform.parent.GetComponentInChildren<FoodSpawner>()`.

2. In the "FoodSpawner" script, update the `SpawnFood()` method to include an optional parameter:

```csharp
public void SpawnFood(int customNumberOfFoods = -1)
{
    // Delete any remaining food
    foreach (var food in GetComponentsInChildren<Food>())
    {
        Destroy(food.gameObject);
    }

    int foodCount = customNumberOfFoods != -1 ? customNumberOfFoods : numberOfFoods;

    for (int i = 0; i < foodCount; i++)
    {
        Vector2 spawnPosition = new Vector2(Random.Range(-spawnRange, spawnRange), Random.Range(-spawnRange, spawnRange));
        GameObject newFood = Instantiate(foodPrefab, spawnPosition, Quaternion.identity, transform);
        newFood.transform.localScale = Vector3.one;
    }
}
```

This adjustment helps agents reference their own "FoodSpawner" when there are multiple Training Areas.

After making these changes, you can use multiple Training Areas without any issues. The agents will move individually within their own Training Area and follow their own time limit defined in their corresponding "FoodSpawner".

In summary, the time limit is set in the Unity editor using the `maxEpisodeTime` variable in the FoodSpawner script, not in the "config.yaml" file, and you can have multiple Training Areas with individual time limits by making the adjustments described above.

Apologies for the confusion. The issue lies in the use of `FindObjectOfType` when searching for the player in the FoodSpawner script. This function returns the first game object it finds with the specified component, which causes all food to spawn within the first Training Area. To fix this issue, ensure that each FoodSpawner spawns food only in its own Training Area.

1. Update the "FoodSpawner" script to use `GetComponentInChildren` to reference the correct player:

```csharp
private void Start()
{
    player = GetComponentInChildren<PlayerController>();

    SpawnFood();
    episodeTimer = maxEpisodeTime;
}
```

By making this change, each FoodSpawner will search for a PlayerController within their own Training Area instead of in the entire scene. This ensures that each Training Area will spawn its own food correctly.

After making this change, duplicate the Training Area, and you will see each area spawns food correctly within its own boundaries.

I apologize for the confusion in my previous solution. The issue actually lies in the use of `FindObjectOfType` in the "PlayerController" script. To fix this, let's change the way we assign the FoodSpawner references in both "FoodSpawner" and "PlayerController" scripts.

1. Update the "PlayerController" script to reference its own "FoodSpawner":

Remove the following lines from the `Start` method:

```csharp
foodSpawner = transform.parent.GetComponentInChildren<FoodSpawner>();
```

Add the following new method in "PlayerController":

```csharp
public void SetFoodSpawner(FoodSpawner spawner)
{
    foodSpawner = spawner;
}
```

2. Update the "FoodSpawner" script to set the FoodSpawner reference in its own "PlayerController":

Update the `Start` method in "FoodSpawner":

```csharp
private void Start()
{
    player = GetComponentInChildren<PlayerController>();
    if (player != null)
    {
        player.SetFoodSpawner(this);
    }

    SpawnFood();
    episodeTimer = maxEpisodeTime;
}
```

After making these changes, duplicate the Training Area with multiple agents in your scene. The food should now spawn in their respective Training Areas.
